Legends involving prominent figures became more historically grounded during the Kamakura period, reflecting improved medical knowledge and the practical benefits of hot springs. For example: * '''Kamakura Period:''' {{ill|Ōtomo Yoriyasu|ja|大友頼泰|12=draft|12=draft}} established hot spring magistrates to develop {{ill|Hamawaki Onsen|ja|浜脇温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Beppu Onsen|ja|別府温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}. * '''Ippen:''' Stopped in Beppu in 1276, discovering {{ill|Tetsu Onsen|ja|鉄輪温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} through a divine message from {{ill|Hi no Kami|ja|火男火売神社|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Legends of Discovery by Animals == Some legends credit animals with discovering onsen, often featuring "white" animals symbolizing purity or divine guidance. These include: * '''Herons:''' {{ill|Gero Onsen|ja|下呂温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yamanaka Onsen|ja|山中温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Dōgo Onsen|ja|道後温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''Cranes:''' {{ill|Kinosaki Onsen|ja|城崎温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''White Foxes:''' {{ill|Yuda Onsen|ja|湯田温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''White Wolves:''' {{ill|Misasa Onsen|ja|三朝温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''Deer:''' {{ill|Yamaga Onsen|ja|山鹿温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kakeyu Onsen|ja|鹿教湯温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''Monkeys:''' {{ill|Tawarayama Onsen|ja|俵山温泉|12=draft|12=draft}} * '''Snakes:''' {{ill|Oigami Onsen|ja|老神温泉|12=draft|12=draft}}
In reality, villagers, hunters, or woodsmen likely discovered the springs after observing animals bathing in them. The association with animals was likely used to make the story more relatable and convincing.
